# Project Structure Rules

## Overview

This is a college learning platform template using MDX. All content must follow the structure and conventions defined here.

## Directory Structure

```
/
├── home.mdx              # Landing page
├── readme.mdx            # Project readme
├── courses/              # All courses
│   └── [course-name]/
│       ├── index.mdx     # Course metadata
│       └── *.mdx         # Chapters
├── guides/               # Standalone guides
│   └── *.mdx
└── assets/               # Images (16:9 banners)
```

## Content Types & Frontmatter

### Course Index (`courses/[name]/index.mdx`)
```yaml
---
title: Course Title              # Required
description: What students learn # Required
banner: ../assets/banner.png     # Optional, 16:9 aspect ratio
---
```

### Guide (`guides/[name].mdx`)
```yaml
---
title: Guide Title               # Required
description: What this teaches   # Required
banner: ../assets/banner.png     # Optional, 16:9 aspect ratio
---
```

### Chapter (course or module chapters)
```yaml
---
title: Chapter Name              # Required
---
```

## Banner Images

- **Aspect ratio:** 16:9 (displayed on feed page)
- **Formats:** png, jpg, jpeg, webp
- **Paths:** 
  - Relative: `../assets/filename.png` or `assets/filename.jpg`
  - Absolute URL: `https://example.com/image.png`
- **Validation:** File must exist in `/assets/` if using relative path

## File Naming

- Use lowercase with hyphens: `intro-to-python`, `web-basics`
- Number chapters for ordering: `1-intro.mdx`, `2-concepts.mdx`
- Be descriptive: `setting-up-environment.mdx` not `setup.mdx`

## Course Organization

**Simple course:**
```
courses/intro-to-python/
  ├── index.mdx
  ├── 1-basics.mdx
  └── 2-variables.mdx
```

**Course with modules:**
```
courses/web-development/
  ├── index.mdx
  ├── 1-html-basics/
  │   ├── index.mdx
  │   ├── 1-structure.mdx
  │   └── 2-elements.mdx
  └── 2-css-styling/
      ├── 3-selectors.mdx
      └── 4-layout.mdx
```

## Guide Creation Workflow

When the user asks to create a new guide, follow this structured process:

### Step 1: Brainstorming
Present **5 possible guide ideas** that:
- Address different skill levels or topics
- Are practical and actionable
- Fit the learning platform's educational goals
- Can be completed in a reasonable reading time

Format:
```
Here are 5 guide ideas:

1. **[Title]** - [Brief description]
2. **[Title]** - [Brief description]
...
```

### Step 2: Discovery Questions
Once the user picks an idea, ask **3-5 follow-up questions** to refine scope:
- Target audience (beginner/intermediate/advanced)?
- Key learning outcomes?
- Specific topics to cover or avoid?
- Preferred length (quick tutorial vs comprehensive guide)?
- Any required prerequisites?

### Step 3: Content Planning
Create a **detailed outline** showing:
- Guide title and description
- Section structure with H2/H3 headings
- Key concepts per section
- Code examples or components to include
- Estimated reading time

Example:
```markdown
## Outline: [Guide Title]

### Introduction
- What problem this solves
- Who this is for

### Section 1: [Topic]
- Concept explanation
- Code example: [description]

### Section 2: [Topic]
...

### Conclusion
- Recap
- Next steps
```

### Step 4: Writing
After approval, write the **complete guide** including:
- Proper frontmatter (title, description, optional banner)
- Following style guidelines (simple English, emojis, clear structure)
- Code examples with syntax highlighting
- Woz component for knowledge checks (if appropriate)
- All content in one go

**File location:** `guides/[guide-name].mdx`

